rComments: One of the best math profs at UTM. He is not easy, but all the resources are there: the textbook (written by him) is cheap and useful, he provides weekly worksheets to get you up to speed about upcoming material (if this "extra" work bothers you, you're in the wrong field of study), etc. Most importantly, he is clear, direct, and approachable

Ali is a great person and a great prof. No doubt MAT301 is a hard course, but if you take first year courses with him, he is a solid choice! His lectures are chill and funny, but be aware of the midterms! He makes you work for it but overall it was an rewarding experience! He is also very accessible and kind outside the classroom.

He expects you to do tons of preview works(almost the whole chapter's reading and exercises before the class), and teach very little himself about textbook content in the class. Instead, he sent out worksheets and review them on class
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: If you are taking MAT102, you definitely want to go to his lectures.
The term tests were very hard. The average was just above 50%. But Ali is a good professor. He explained concepts very clearly on lectures.

This professor gives you tones of homework for one class. And this homework assignment is nothing related to midterms and finals. This professor thinks that you are only taking one class for the semester. I worked so hard solving all questions but ended up failing. I will never take a class with him.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Great prof, really good at explaining concepts, keeping the mood light in the classroom and super patient with students. tests completely reflect the reviews they give and final exam wasn't the hardest thing ever and I only studied the day before.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Hilarious']

rComments: very nice guy but doesn't explain concepts well. The tests were HARD so pay attention

He's a great prof, he does his best to explain to his students. He also leaves some exercises in his lectures that are kinda similar to the questions you might see on the exam. I've had him for Mat137 & MAT102, and I would love to have him again in my upper years.
HIlarious Prof, He knows how to teach and keep it interesting. I never get bored in his class even if i dont know what's going on. He keeps it very engaging and i look forward for his classes
sickest prof in UTM
would recommend for MAT102. Very chill prof and is always open to questions during class. Do not skip class or you will be lost.

He's not a difficult professor, it's just the nature of the course. He'll boggle your mind, teaches well and is hysterical. PARTICIPATION MATTERS: if you get lost while he's lecturing ASK QUESTIONS or ASK HIM to slow down. His TAs are awesome. If there's a single thing you don't understand, go to TA office hours/FSGs. Practice makes perfect.
Great
My favorite prof at utm, very good at explaining any confusion and always wants students to ask questions
He provides examples that are going to be quite similar on the quizzes.  He just needs to slow down most of the time.

rComments: Amazing prof! Interesting lectures..
amazing prof!! very interesting classes.

Can't say much about "easiness", since all profs (FALL 2015) write a portion of the test questions.  However, I can vouch for "clarity", since students from Tvalavadze's class were coming to Ali's instead. He won't move forward unless you participate--and he likes to play devil's advocate, so expect him to ask counter-questions; don't be offended.

He is a really harsh professor (and is quite intimidating) but he teaches very well.  This course is all about NOT looking at the answers, especially when you have been banging your head on the desk for over an hour.
